WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:02.340
- Here with Jennifer Mitchell from Gander Social.

00:00:02.350 --> 00:00:03.250
- Thank you.

00:00:03.290 --> 00:00:04.840
It was a good reminder to introduce myself.

00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:06.840
I am Jennifer Mitchell from Gander Social.

00:00:06.850 --> 00:00:07.680
Thank you.

00:00:07.690 --> 00:00:11.720
So, Gander Social, why do we even exist?

00:00:11.730 --> 00:00:14.900
Because who wants another social media network?

00:00:14.910 --> 00:00:17.470
So, hey, we've got one person does, so

00:00:17.470 --> 00:00:18.470
that's good for us.

00:00:18.490 --> 00:00:20.710
Nice.

00:00:20.730 --> 00:00:24.460
So over the last few years, Canadians have started noticing something

00:00:24.490 --> 00:00:26.520
like a little fishy.

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:33.940
And almost every place where we talk online is owned somewhere else

00:00:33.940 --> 00:00:33.940
.

00:00:33.950 --> 00:00:37.760
And that somewhere else is the United States, mostly.

00:00:37.770 --> 00:00:40.890
Which worked fine, or at least we pretended it worked fine

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:41.960
for a while.

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:46.080
But when that country starts talking about annexation and turning us

00:00:46.130 --> 00:00:48.990
into the 51st state, it suddenly feels a little bit

00:00:48.990 --> 00:00:53.760
strange that all of our national conversations happen on their infrastructure and

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:57.110
what a risk that would be to us if they did suddenly

00:00:57.230 --> 00:01:00.430
, you know, take their own threats seriously, which we

00:01:00.510 --> 00:01:01.290
certainly do.

00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:04.400
So that realization led our founder, Ben Wallman, he

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:05.140
's over there.

00:01:05.150 --> 00:01:06.300
You can talk to him here.

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:10.270
To ask a simple question, what would it look like if

00:01:10.270 --> 00:01:14.280
Canadians had a social network that was truly ours?

00:01:14.290 --> 00:01:19.880
So not isolationist, but just digital sovereignty and choice.

00:01:19.890 --> 00:01:23.640
And that idea became Gander Social.

00:01:23.650 --> 00:01:27.410
So when we started researching how to build this kind of sovereign

00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:30.680
social space, we realized something very quickly.

00:01:30.690 --> 00:01:33.810
If we were going to build a closed platform, we would

00:01:33.810 --> 00:01:37.380
recreate the exact problems that we were trying to solve.

00:01:37.390 --> 00:01:41.100
And so then Ben discovered the app protocol.

00:01:41.110 --> 00:01:44.270
So an interesting thing is that for us, the problem came

00:01:44.270 --> 00:01:47.770
first and app protocol came second, which is kind of a

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:49.610
different story, I think, to a lot of the other

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:51.810
companies building on the protocol today.

00:01:51.850 --> 00:01:54.340
But what really excited us about the protocol was three things.

00:01:54.350 --> 00:01:56.670
So one was user portability.

00:01:56.690 --> 00:02:01.090
So we very firmly wanted the users to have control over their

00:02:01.100 --> 00:02:01.780
own data.

00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:02.760
We don't want their data.

00:02:02.770 --> 00:02:04.560
If we could know nothing about them, that would be the

00:02:04.620 --> 00:02:07.620
preference because then now we're a low risk target and now

00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:09.170
there's no risk that we're ever going to sell it

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:12.380
on to any person or company in the future.

00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:15.620
So user portability was a massive one for us.

00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:18.720
The second one was, of course, the interoperability

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:18.820
.

00:02:18.830 --> 00:02:22.010
You know, if you're building any kind of new social

00:02:22.010 --> 00:02:24.020
network, the empty room is a big issue.

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:27.450
And so having that interoperability into an existing data layer

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:32.260
would be incredibly helpful, but also recognizing what the future potential

00:02:32.270 --> 00:02:34.360
of that was going to be for us.

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:38.320
And then third, which is even more interesting for us because

00:02:38.410 --> 00:02:41.380
we have equal amount of supporters and attractors for how we

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:44.300
're doing this, is permissionless innovation.

00:02:44.330 --> 00:02:47.460
So the fact that we can build what we want on the

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:51.500
protocol without having to go and ask for permission is actually quite

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:52.360
a big deal.

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:55.180
And it really kind of pushes forward what we could potentially do

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:55.360
.

00:02:55.370 --> 00:02:57.820
So we didn't really see the protocol as just infrastructure.

00:02:57.830 --> 00:03:00.860
We saw it as alignment with our values.

00:03:00.870 --> 00:03:03.700
So we solved that.

00:03:03.710 --> 00:03:06.270
And then we have to figure out what our users actually want

00:03:06.310 --> 00:03:06.480
.

00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:09.430
And the thing is, it's like the people using G

00:03:09.430 --> 00:03:10.740
ander today fall into two groups.

00:03:10.750 --> 00:03:13.070
So right now we're in a closed beta.

00:03:13.090 --> 00:03:15.670
We ideally would have been out of that beta by this conference

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:18.380
, but Apple liked to wait to give, you know,

00:03:18.390 --> 00:03:21.350
approval on your production app, and so we wait.

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:25.230
But we've got about 9,000 people in a closed

00:03:25.230 --> 00:03:29.360
beta and about 30,000 people knocking down the doors to

00:03:29.410 --> 00:03:30.870
try and get in.

00:03:30.910 --> 00:03:32.580
And they fall into two groups.

00:03:32.590 --> 00:03:34.960
So we have one group who have heard of Blue Sky,

00:03:34.970 --> 00:03:38.500
maybe they're on Blue Sky, and they understand the atmosphere

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:39.360
ecosystem.

00:03:39.370 --> 00:03:42.670
And then the other group haven't heard of either, nor

00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:43.850
do they care.

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:47.830
And the majority of the people on there are in that second

00:03:47.830 --> 00:03:48.560
group.

00:03:48.570 --> 00:03:54.020
And so what they want is actually deceptively simple,

00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:55.500
deceptively simple.

00:03:55.510 --> 00:03:58.950
They want to meaningfully connect with other humans.

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:03.360
They want accessible, familiar features that are easy to use.

00:04:03.370 --> 00:04:06.140
And they want to reach their audiences, whether they're creators

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:08.510
or businesses or whoever that is.

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:12.410
And they want somewhere that they can trust again and somewhere that

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:14.120
feels safe and civil.

00:04:14.130 --> 00:04:19.350
So our focus at Gander is actually delivering those familiar features

00:04:19.450 --> 00:04:22.060
, hopefully with a pro-social twist that we continue to

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:28.340
experiment with on actual sovereign infrastructure, but we still benefit from

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:31.200
the interoperability of the protocol underneath that.

00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:37.530
And so, no, we're not going anywhere.

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:41.560
No, we went too far.

00:04:41.570 --> 00:04:42.400
Great.

00:04:42.410 --> 00:04:49.360
So the promise of the protocol is interoperability.

00:04:49.370 --> 00:04:53.050
But when we were discussing this user choice, this user agency

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:54.930
, all of these things we wanted to give people, we

00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:58.710
realized that we can't force interoperability onto people as

00:04:58.710 --> 00:04:59.900
individuals.

00:04:59.910 --> 00:05:02.980
And so who decides how interoperable you are as an

00:05:03.070 --> 00:05:04.240
individual?

00:05:04.250 --> 00:05:07.380
And our answer always comes back to the user has to decide

00:05:07.390 --> 00:05:07.580
.

00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:11.460
And so on Gander, users will be able to choose

00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:14.190
their level of participation in the wider atmosphere.

00:05:14.230 --> 00:05:18.560
And so for example, if a user wants to post only

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:21.850
a small group, what we're currently calling nests.

00:05:21.870 --> 00:05:24.350
Because, you know, Gander, geese, the

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:27.860
puns are endless.

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:29.850
Or they want to post just inside Gander, or they

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:32.470
want to post to the entire atmosphere, they can choose to

00:05:32.470 --> 00:05:33.170
do that.

00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:35.660
And the same applies to what they see.

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:38.260
So if they want to view a private social circle, they

00:05:38.310 --> 00:05:40.580
want to view Gander-only content, or they want

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:43.820
to, again, view and have access to the entire atmosphere

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:45.540
, they choose that.

00:05:45.550 --> 00:05:48.640
So on-screen is just an example of someone's settings

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:51.530
where they're choosing to view Gander in their feeds and

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:52.860
also Blue Sky in their feeds.

00:05:52.870 --> 00:05:56.060
And the intention is to open that up to everybody who's

00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:59.190
participating in the atmosphere, so the users can toggle on and

00:05:59.190 --> 00:06:03.000
off what content they want to receive.

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:05.480
Because some of our users really, really, really love the

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:06.800
open atmosphere.

00:06:06.810 --> 00:06:10.230
And other users want a quieter space where they're just focused

00:06:10.230 --> 00:06:11.200
on friends and family.

00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:14.240
And both of those choices are valid.

00:06:14.250 --> 00:06:16.210
And we're not going to make that choice for them.

00:06:16.230 --> 00:06:19.890
So our philosophy is very, very simple, which is inter

00:06:19.890 --> 00:06:21.780
operability by choice.

00:06:21.790 --> 00:06:27.620
So one of the biggest challenges social media faces is that today

00:06:27.620 --> 00:06:28.620
is a collapse of trust.

00:06:28.630 --> 00:06:30.180
So of course, we were like, well, let's

00:06:30.180 --> 00:06:33.560
make it sovereign, but let's also make it better.

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:36.500
What an opportunity to take.

00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:38.250
And so at the moment, we've got bots, we

00:06:38.250 --> 00:06:40.950
've got coordinated manipulation, we've got disinformation, we

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:44.450
've got harassment, and many networks try to fix these problems

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:46.640
after the fact.

00:06:46.650 --> 00:06:48.820
And we wanted to design systems that help prevent them in the

00:06:48.870 --> 00:06:49.480
first place.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:52.580
So we think about Gander as an experiment in pro-

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:55.620
social design, several systems working together.

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:59.300
So first, we have our human verification, which we are

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:02.420
planning to do through Canada Post's Identity Verification Service

00:07:02.420 --> 00:07:02.420
.

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:07.180
And in a nutshell, the verification happens entirely on device with

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:09.730
Canada Post's verification system, including being able to walk into

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:12.700
your local post office and verify that you are a human being

00:07:12.700 --> 00:07:12.930
.

00:07:12.950 --> 00:07:16.040
We never receive identity documents, nor do we want them,

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:17.040
quite frankly.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:20.440
We just receive a signal confirming someone is human and someone is

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:21.570
over 18.

00:07:21.590 --> 00:07:23.870
And so someone is already on the beta.

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:25.220
It's not like that now.

00:07:25.230 --> 00:07:30.060
But very shortly, if you want to engage on Gander

00:07:30.060 --> 00:07:31.840
, so you want to post, comment, et cetera,

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:33.730
you are going to have to verify that you're a human

00:07:33.730 --> 00:07:34.800
being in over 18.

00:07:34.810 --> 00:07:37.770
Otherwise, you get a view only access to it.

00:07:37.810 --> 00:07:41.920
And that small amount of friction that we are deliberately introducing is

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:45.940
going to help us discourage bots and coordinated abuse.

00:07:45.950 --> 00:07:48.580
So our second then is moderation infrastructure.

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:51.020
We're running our own instance of ozone and we have our

00:07:51.080 --> 00:07:54.800
own moderation policies that are in line with Canadian law and the

00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:56.390
Charter of Human Rights and Freedoms, which is

00:07:56.470 --> 00:07:57.960
incredibly important here.

00:07:57.970 --> 00:07:59.150
We have freedom of expression.

00:07:59.170 --> 00:08:00.480
We don't have free speech.

00:08:00.490 --> 00:08:04.200
That distinction is important and it makes it a safer space to

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:04.420
be.

00:08:04.430 --> 00:08:05.800
And also information integrity.

00:08:05.810 --> 00:08:09.940
So we integrate media bias indicators and source factuality signals,

00:08:09.950 --> 00:08:13.400
giving users more context when they encounter information.

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:18.340
So what have we built so far?

00:08:18.350 --> 00:08:19.840
Little snapshots all over.

00:08:19.850 --> 00:08:20.720
I'll give you a list.

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:21.340
I'll read it out.

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:22.250
We have text posts.

00:08:22.290 --> 00:08:23.190
We have images.

00:08:23.250 --> 00:08:25.320
We have vertical video scrolling.

00:08:25.330 --> 00:08:27.560
Like on TikTok, we have boards like Pinterest.

00:08:27.570 --> 00:08:28.420
We have feeds.

00:08:28.430 --> 00:08:30.180
We have direct messages.

00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:34.690
We also support multiple feeds, allowing different ways to experience content

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:34.960
.

00:08:34.970 --> 00:08:37.690
Like I said, we've already deployed our own ozone moderation

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:40.410
instance, the media bias and fact checking integrations, and

00:08:40.410 --> 00:08:45.040
we're preparing to test the human verification very shortly.

00:08:45.050 --> 00:08:48.160
We have 8,000, almost 9,000 beta test

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:48.340
ers.

00:08:48.350 --> 00:08:50.040
Now 30,000 people waiting to get in.

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:52.610
And once all of those folks are in, everybody gets invite

00:08:52.610 --> 00:08:54.280
codes to invite their friends and family.

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:57.130
We are deliberately not doing a big splashy launch because we

00:08:57.130 --> 00:09:00.780
want this to come out sustainably and thoughtfully.

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:03.380
So what does it feel like on Gander right now?

00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:07.080
It's an example of a few little bits.

00:09:07.090 --> 00:09:09.940
This has been a big one for us.

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:12.710
So it turns out when you change the structure of a social

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:16.700
network, you can actually fundamentally change the culture of the conversation

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:16.700
.

00:09:16.710 --> 00:09:20.100
And people are really noticing that Gander is different.

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:21.460
It's a little slower.

00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:22.500
It's a little more human.

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:24.830
All our feeds are chronological.

00:09:24.850 --> 00:09:27.210
And it feels a little bit more like the early days of

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:28.120
social media.

00:09:28.150 --> 00:09:31.220
And that is something that we are going to try to continue

00:09:31.230 --> 00:09:34.530
to, you know, hopefully it will persist as we get

00:09:34.530 --> 00:09:36.020
bigger.

00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:38.300
So while we've built the features and the infrastructure, we

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:40.960
're also starting to see something else emerge.

00:09:40.970 --> 00:09:47.700
So a community culture that is more civil and more intentional.

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:50.560
I'm running out of time, so I might skip the

00:09:50.570 --> 00:09:51.440
next bit.

00:09:51.450 --> 00:09:53.650
Basically, for a long time, social media has been something

00:09:53.650 --> 00:09:54.300
we were given.

00:09:54.310 --> 00:09:55.840
So platforms told us what it would be.

00:09:55.850 --> 00:09:57.540
Algorithms told us what we would see.

00:09:57.550 --> 00:10:00.580
And we think the next phase should look very different.

00:10:00.590 --> 00:10:05.490
And networks where users have real choice, where we can build

00:10:05.540 --> 00:10:09.440
communities, ecosystems where developers build together, and Gander is

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:12.750
just one experiment in that future, and hopefully one that will

00:10:12.750 --> 00:10:13.400
persist.

00:10:13.410 --> 00:10:16.840
And we're excited to build it in the atmosphere.

00:10:16.850 --> 00:10:19.630
Thank you.
